TITLE: The National Archives is looking into reports that the Secret Service deleted texts
SUMMARY: Reports that the Secret Service deleted text messages related to Jan. 6 Capitol insurrection have caught the attention of the chief records officer at the National Archives.

TITLE: Twitter's lawsuit against Elon Musk will go to trial in October
SUMMARY: A Delaware judge ruled the trial will last for five days in October, giving Twitter an early victory in its legal battle against the Tesla CEO. The company had argued that any delay would hurt it.

TITLE: Toys R Us is making another comeback — this time in Macy's stores
SUMMARY: Macy's is making room for Toys R Us shops within its own stores ahead of the holiday season. After struggling financially, the longtime toy chain shuttered its stores in 2018.

TITLE: The 2021 rise in U.S. births is likely a baby blip, not a boom
SUMMARY: The U.S. birth rate has been trending downwards over the past 15 years — so the news that the number of births actually rose in 2021 is making headlines.

TITLE: Millions of kids qualify for Medicaid. Biden funds outreach to boost enrollment
SUMMARY: More than half of uninsured kids qualify for free coverage but don't know it. The government has released $49 million to get the word out, especially as the end of the COVID health emergency looms.

TITLE: An amusement park Haunted Mansion delivers summer screams and lifelong memories
SUMMARY: At an old-school amusement park in Rehoboth Beach, Del., called Funland, a generation of thrillseekers who grew up screaming in the park's Haunted Mansion now brings their kids to do the same.

TITLE: Emmett Till's Chicago home will get money designated for preserving Black history
SUMMARY: A preservation organization said the home will get a share of $3 million in grants being distributed to 33 sites and organizations nationwide that are important pieces of African American history.

TITLE: Indiana's AG could face a lawsuit by the abortion provider for 10-year-old rape victim
SUMMARY: Dr. Caitlin Bernard has threatened to sue Republican Attorney General Todd Rokita for "false and misleading statements" he made after she provided a medication abortion for the girl from Ohio.

TITLE: Beads, felt and bark are turned into masterpieces at Smithsonian Folklife Festival
SUMMARY: This summer, artisans from Kenya, Mongolia and Uganda shared the story of their centuries-old traditional crafts — including the art of "barkcloth," declared a UNESCO world heritage "masterpiece."

TITLE: Jan. 6 panel chair Thompson to miss Thursday's hearing after testing COVID positive
SUMMARY: Rep. Bennie Thompson, who is fully vaccinated and boosted, said he is experiencing mild symptoms. He has instructed the Jan. 6 committee to proceed with Thursday evening's hearing without him.

TITLE: Have you been involved with a state or federal execution? We want to hear from you.
SUMMARY: If you witnessed or helped conduct an execution in the United States, reporters at NPR would like to talk with you.

TITLE: Sesame Place apologizes after video shows 2 Black girls being passed over at a parade
SUMMARY: In its apology, Sesame Place Philadelphia said its employees will undergo more training after criticism over a video in which an employee in costume appeared to ignore two Black girls during a parade.

TITLE: Reproductive care continues in Montgomery, Ala., despite women's clinic closing
SUMMARY: The POWER House, which opened in 2015 next door to a now-closed clinic that performed abortions, continues to see clients, offering them sexual information and contraception.

TITLE: Biden issues a new executive order relating to hostages and detained Americans
SUMMARY: President Biden has issued an executive order to try to improve efforts to free American hostages and detainees, senior administration officials told reporters.

TITLE: Yellen believes U.S. will get on board with global minimum corporate tax — eventually
SUMMARY: Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen spoke to <em>Morning Edition
